[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/asp-net-core] While current Microsoft Edge works, the legacy version of it, i.e.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/asp-net-core] "Microsoft Edge Legacy" and Internet Explorer 11 was dropped when you use Blazor.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/asp-net-core] Originally deemed **ASP.NET vNext**, the framework was going to be called **ASP.NET 5** when ready.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/asp-net-core] However, in order to avoid implying it is an update to the existing ASP.NET framework, Microsoft later changed the name to ASP.NET Core at the 1.0 release.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:aspnet-libs-dotnet/web-application] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
